text:
The husband, a thick-set, healthy man in evening dress, was drinking off
      neat whisky. He put down his tumbler, and deliberately struck a match;
      then with even greater deliberation he lit a gold-tipped cigarette....

"I can't conceive what you're -- in such a hurry for;
      you 're not going to be married till the autumn," said Mr.
      Paramor, finishing at last.

"St. Briabas; two-thirty. Come and see how they do the trick. I'll
      call for you at one; we'll have some lunch and go together";
      again he patted Benjy's knee.

Crocker took hold of his arm above the elbow, and, squeezing it, he
      grunted. Shelton had not received congratulations that pleased him more;
      there was the spice of envy in them.

"You 're hungry, I expect, after your tramp. I'm very
      much afraid there 's -- er -- nothing in the house but bread;
      I could boil you water; hot lemonade is better than nothing."

"I think I shall do a bit more walking to-night," he said;
      "I feel very fit. Don't you really mean to come any further
      with me, Bird?"

"But I did n't speak to her first," he told himself;
      "I shall only be telling a lie, and they 'll make me swear it,
      too!"

It was somewhat late that afternoon when Shelton had his "wigging";
      nor did it seem to him, hypnotised by the momentary absence of Antonia,
      such a very serious affair.

"You 'll be with us for that dinner-party next week, eh?
      Capital! There's the Bishop of Blumenthal and old Sir Jack Buckwell;
      I must get my wife to put you between them -- "

Once again his utterance enfolded all as with a blessing, and once again
      the world fell into its three departments: that where they do you well;
      that where they do you better; and -- Baghdad.

"What price that?" he said, as he regained the perpendicular;
      and his well-fed eyes followed Shelton with sleepy inquisition. "Curious
      dark horse, Shelton," they seemed to say.

As a fact, however, he was far from seeing; he literally did not know what
      to do. It seemed so brutal to give Ferrand money and ask him to clear out;
      besides, he chanced to have none in his pocket.

"I should hate to live in London," said Antonia suddenly;
      "the slums must be so awful. What a pity, when there are places like
      this! But it's no good thinking."

"Yes," echoed Mr. Dennant; "he 's had some
      singular experience. If you want to know the details, ask friend Shelton;
      it's quite romantic. In the meantime, my dear; another cup?"

"Ah!" thought Shelton, in the dreamy way of tired people;
      "the institutions are all right; it's the spirit that's
      all -- "
